590s by Moderata Fonte, pseudonym of the Renaissance poet and writer Modesta Pozzo, this literary dialogue interrogates men and men’s treatment of women, and explores by contrast the virtues of singledom and female friendship. As the women diverge from their theme—discussing everything from astrology to the curative powers of plants and minerals—a remarkable group portrait of wisdom, wit, and erudition emerges. A new introduction by translator Virginia Cox and foreword by Dacia Maraini situate The Merits of Women in its historical context, written as it was on the cusp of Shakespeare’s heyday, and straddling the centuries between the feminist works of Christine de Pizan and Mary Wollstonecraft. Elegantly presented for a general audience, this is a must-read for baby feminists and “nasty women” alike, not to mention the perfect subtle gift for any mansplaining friend who needs a refresher on the merits of women . . . and their superiority to men.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aWomenvEarly works to 1800. 0aWomenxHistoryyRenaissance, 1450-1600. 0aWomenxSocial conditionsvEarly works to 1800. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aCox, Virginia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCox, Virginia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDoglioni, Giovanni Niccolò, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaraini, Dacia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaraini, Dacia.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311068858040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226550770423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226550770.jpg  a978-3-11-068858-0  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alle